The '''''Wild Cat''''' is a fictional green two-masted [[schooner]] that [[Captain Flint#In other works|Captain Flint]], the Swallows, the Amazons and Peter Duck sail to the [[West Indies]] in [[Arthur Ransome]]'s [[Swallows and Amazons series|Swallows and Amazons]] book ''[[Peter Duck]]''. She also appears in the opening chapters of ''[[Missee Lee]]''.
The ship would have been about 50 [[Foot (length)|ft]] (15 m) long. In the book and the illustrations there is no mention of a [[head (watercraft)|head]]. This is typical of Arthur Ransome's reticence on the issue. 

The name is taken from Wild Cat Island which features in all the [[Swallows and Amazons series|books]] set in the [[Lake District]]. She was converted from a [[Baltic Sea|Baltic]] trading [[schooner]] by decking over the hold to make a saloon with a long skylight and four double cabins opening into it. The deckhouse has a couple of bunks which are used by the adults, Captain Flint and Peter Duck, in the book ''Peter Duck''.<ref>Ransome, Arthur, ''Peter Duck'', Chapter 1</ref> 

In Ransome's book ''[[Missee Lee]]'', the ship was burned to the waterline and sinks when Gibber, Roger's monkey, put a lighted cigar in the fuel (petrol) holding tank. In ''Peter Duck'', the ''Swallow'' is aboard and is used as one of the ship's boats. In ''Missee Lee'', both the ''Swallow'' and ''Amazon'' are aboard and used as lifeboats when she sinks.<ref>Ransome, Arthur, ''Missee Lee'', Chapter 2</ref>

